# dd-demo-toolkit configuration
# =============================
#
# This file holds **references** to secrets, not the secrets themselves.
# Plain-text Datadog keys here violate the corp secret-handling policy.
# Full walkthrough lives in README § "Handling secrets" — read that for
# desktop-app vs CLI signin, vault/item creation, and rotation steps.
#
# Quick reference:
#   - Install op CLI:   brew install --cask 1password-cli
#   - Auth probe:       op vault list      (NOT `op whoami` — unreliable
#                                            under desktop biometric auth)
#   - Verify this file: op run --env-file=.env -- env | grep -cE "^DD_.*=op://"
#                       (expected: 0 — every reference resolved)
#   - Run commands:     make up / make setup / make ui  (all auto-wrap in op run)
#
# Common pitfall when editing this file or running `op item create`:
# **smart quotes**. If you paste a command from chat / a doc / a wiki and
# get an unclosed-quote error from your shell, look for `'` `'` `"` `"`
# (curly) instead of `'` `"` (ASCII). Type apostrophes by hand. macOS
# System Settings → Keyboard → Text → uncheck "Use smart quotes" prevents
# the auto-substitution.

# ---- Secrets (stored in 1Password, NOT here) --------------------------------
#
# Format: op://<vault>/<item>/<field>
#
# Default values below assume you have a 1Password item titled "Datadog"
# in the "Employee" vault with four fields. Edit the paths to match your
# actual vault/item names if different. Field labels (api-key, app-key,
# client-token, rum-application-id) must match exactly — lowercase,
# hyphenated, no spaces. Verify with:
#
#     for f in api-key app-key client-token rum-application-id; do \
#         echo "$f: $(op read op://Employee/Datadog/$f | wc -c) bytes"; \
#     done
#
# Putting a plain-text key here is a policy violation; the web UI's
# save endpoint will reject it, and `docker compose` will see the
# literal `op://...` and fail with a `${VAR:?}` error if you bypass
# the Makefile.
DD_API_KEY=op://Employee/Datadog/api-key
DD_APP_KEY=op://Employee/Datadog/app-key

# Optional: RUM client-side telemetry credentials. The toolkit doesn't
# emit RUM directly today (the simulator's `rum.py` ships data through
# OTel), but the env vars are reserved for future client-integration
# phases. Uncomment + fill in if you're wiring up a browser-side demo.
#
# DD_CLIENT_TOKEN is a SECRET — Datadog docs say it's safe to embed in
# client-side JS, but corp policy still requires vault storage. Use an
# op:// reference; the UI rejects plain values for this key.
#
# DD_RUM_APPLICATION_ID is a UUID identifier (not a secret — literally
# shipped to every browser via the RUM init snippet) but kept vaulted
# for centralized rotation. The UI accepts a plain UUID here too.
# DD_CLIENT_TOKEN=op://Employee/Datadog/client-token
# DD_RUM_APPLICATION_ID=op://Employee/Datadog/rum-application-id

# ---- Non-secret config ------------------------------------------------------

# Your Datadog site (datadoghq.com for US1, us3.datadoghq.com, datadoghq.eu, ...)
DD_SITE=datadoghq.com

# Vertical selection (healthcare, finance, manufacturing, insurance, hospitality)
DD_DEMO_VERTICAL=healthcare

# Optional: sub-vertical overlay. Layered additively on the base vertical.
# Currently shipped: `bd`, `quest`, `adventhealth` on top of `healthcare`.
# Comment out for base only.
# DD_DEMO_SUB_VERTICAL=bd

# Optional: products/features to demonstrate (comma-separated). Set via the
# UI's "Products & features to demonstrate" checkbox picker; captures the
# demo's intended scope for setup and downstream asset filtering. Selecting
# `dbm` here makes the UI also set DD_DEMO_DBM=true (below).
# DD_DEMO_PRODUCTS=apm,logs,infra,eud,bits

# Optional: enable the DBM (Database Monitoring) stack — postgres + dedicated
# Datadog Agent + SQL workload generator. Works with any vertical/sub-vertical.
# Automatically enabled when DD_DEMO_SUB_VERTICAL=payment-processor.
# DD_DEMO_DBM=true

# Optional: enable the Sensing Hospital mock app — a real containerized
# microservice app + mock IoT edge fleet collected by the ACTUAL Datadog Agent
# (APM service map, traces, logs, process/container infra). Mirrors the
# AdventHealth overlay's on-prem→cloud care-experience cascade. When true,
# `make up` brings it along; or run it standalone with `make up-mock-app`.
# DD_DEMO_MOCK_FLEET=true

# Optional: Datadog Synthetics private location for driving traffic at the
# mock app's RUM frontend (public managed locations can't reach localhost).
# 1) Create a private location in Datadog (Synthetics > Settings > Private
#    Locations). 2) Paste the JSON config blob it returns here, and the
#    location id (pl:...) below. 3) `make up-synthetics && make synthetics-create`.
# DATADOG_PRIVATE_LOCATION_CONFIG={"id":"pl:...","site":"...","privateKey":"...","publicKey":{...},"accessKey":"...","secretAccessKey":"..."}
# DD_SYNTHETICS_PRIVATE_LOCATION_ID=pl:xxxxxxxxxxxxx

# Simulator settings — seconds between metric/log emissions.
EMIT_INTERVAL=15

# Optional: custom display name shown in Datadog instead of the vertical name.
# DISPLAY_NAME=My Custom Demo
